0.13672197,0.00351796,-0.03877085,0.06520195,0.06638978,0.03547562,0.01478270,0.04543611,0.00759164,-0.03835816,0.02487779,0.03330420,0.02432753,0.01803889,-0.03594548,-0.01366658,-0.01901510,0.04703504,-0.04667166,0.04135857,-0.02757494,-0.03501721,0.05987034,0.00175678,-0.07378027,-0.06509064,-0.02335909,0.02824463,-0.06999747,-0.06954491,0.03254056,-0.00094363,-0.04994547,0.04874111,-0.00524769,-0.01729116,0.04665117,0.03278831,0.09736197,-0.02336300,0.00978459,-0.01766499,0.01291501]',E'Monotonic clock\n\nBy default, Redis will build using the POSIX clock_gettime function as the monotonic clock source. On most modern systems, the internal processor clock can be used to improve performance. Cautions can be found here: http://oliveryang.net/2015/09/pitfalls-of-TSC-usage/\n\nOn ARM aarch64 systems, the hardware clock is enabled by default because the ARM Generic Timer is architecturally guaranteed to be available and monotonic on all ARMv8-A processors (see the *“The Generic Timer in AArch64 state”* section of the *Arm Architecture Reference Manual for Armv8-A*).\n\nTo build with support for the processor''s internal instruction clock on other architectures, use:\n\n```sh\nmake CFLAGS="-DUSE_PROCESSOR_CLOCK"\n```','{"source": "redis", "version": "7.4", "language": "nosql", "title": "Readme", "section_title": "README", "url": "https://github.com/redis/redis/blob/unstable/README.md", "topics": "redis,README", "categories": "database,nosql,cache"}');
